         <abstract>
            <p>The purpose of this paper is to investigate the application of the finite element method of Lagrange multipliers to the problem of approximating the eigenvalues of a selfadjoint elliptic operator satisfying Dirichlet boundary conditions. Although the Lagrange multiplier method is not a Rayleigh-Ritz-Galerkin approximation scheme, it is shown that at least asymptotically the Lagrange multiplier method has some of the properties of such a scheme. In particular, the approximate eigenvalues are greater than or equal to the exact eigenvalues and can be computed from a nonnegative definite matrix problem. It is also shown that the known estimates for the eigenvalue error are optimal.</p>
          </abstract>
